@pipermerriam also at this point `.formatting` is looking pretty scarce
```python
def pad_left(value, to_size, pad_with):
    """
    Should be called to pad value to expected length
    """
    return value.rjust(to_size, pad_with)

def pad_right(value, to_size, pad_with):
    """
    Should be called to pad value to expected length
    """
    return value.ljust(to_size, pad_with)

def is_prefixed(value, prefix):
    return value.startswith(prefix)
```
@carver suggested deprecating these functions and using the stdlib functions - which i think makes sense now

We are passing same `aBuf` for input/output to `Decrypt/Encrypt` methods which would then do in-place operation.
How about if we change the definitions to expect a single buffer and also pass it the max size of the buffer as argument

```
// aFrameBuf : Pointer to buffer containing the frame, also where the encrypted frame will be placed
// aFrameSize : Max number of bytes in frame buffer.
// aFrameLength: Pointer to store frame length, on input value is set to frame length, 
//              on output changed to show the frame length after decryption.
bool EncryptOutbound(unsigned char *aFrameBuf, size_t aFrameSize,  size_t *aFrameLength)
````

Thoughts?
